Use ASP.NET Core's `WebApplicationFactory<T>` — it hosts your app in-memory with a full HTTP pipeline but no real network listener.

**1. Add the test package:**
```
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
```

**2. Write a test class:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using System.Text.Json;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26", body.GetProperty("result")
            .GetProperty("protocolVersion").GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_ExecutesTool()
    {
        // Initialize first
        await InitializeSession();

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new
            {
                name = "my_tool",
                arguments = new { input = "hello" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.False(body.GetProperty("result")
            .GetProperty("isError").GetBoolean());
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `WebApplicationFactory<Program>` boots your real `Program.cs` pipeline in-process — middleware, DI, routing all execute as in production.
- No port binding, no process management, no flaky network issues.
- Use `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => ...)` to swap dependencies (e.g., inject a mock database) for isolated tests.
- If your MCP server uses SSE for streaming, test that endpoint separately by reading the response stream with `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead`.

**For Streamable HTTP (session-based):**

```csharp
// Preserve the Mcp-Session-Id header across requests
var initResponse = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", initRequest);
var sessionId = initResponse.Headers.GetValues("Mcp-Session-Id").First();

_client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Mcp-Session-Id", sessionId);
// Subsequent requests now target the same session
```

This gives you full protocol-level coverage (JSON-RPC framing, error codes, capability negotiation) with fast, deterministic tests.
